<HEAD>
<TITLE>Studies on Religion, Economy Available</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<CENTER><H2>Studies on Religion, Economy Available</H2></CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<P>
The Media Research Center has produced a new landmark study of how news and 
entertainment television treat religion. Faith in a Box, 1994 builds on the 
1993 study of the same name, which found that religion received poor treatment 
in both the news and on prime time.
In the 1994 study, the MRC found marked improvement in Hollywood's depiction of 
religion, but network news continued to trivialize or downplay religious 
themes.
<P>
As was the case with its 1993 predecessor, Faith in a Box, 1994 was recently 
released to the media in Hollywood and Washington, and distributed to 
conservative and religious activists nationwide.
<P>
Leaders in the entertainment industry, including network executives, have been 
briefed on the MRC's findings as well, and given the MRC's recommendations on 
improving religious portrayals on their television shows.
<P>
To obtain a copy of Faith in a Box, 1994, please call 1-800-MRC-1423 or write 
to us at: Media Research Center, 113 S. West Street, Suite 200, Alexandria, VA 
22314.
<P>
MediaNomics readers still have a chance to obtain Out of Focus: Network 
Television and the American Economy by MediaNomics editor Burton Yale Pines, as 
well.
<P>
Out of Focus takes an in-depth look at an entire year's network reporting on 
such as issues as health care reform, environmental policy, taxes, government 
spending, business, and consumer affairs. The book also looks into the impact 
of prime-time entertainment television on the culture of free enterprise and 
business.
<P>
According to the Richmond Times-Dispatch, "Out of Focus is a major blast at 
American network television. It deserves the attention of thinking Americans."
National Review agreed: "Out of Focus does for TV viewers what Consumer Reports 
does for car buyers, exposing the recurring flaws in the reports of Ray Brady, 
Irving R. Levine, most of the CNN staff, and the like."
<P>
To obtain a copy of Out of Focus: Network Television and the American Economy, 
call 1-800-243-BIAS.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BODY>
</HTML>
