<HTML>
<HEAD>
<CENTER><TITLE><b><i>Flash</i></b>: Media Research Center's Monthly Member's Report</TITLE></CENTER>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" 
<U><CENTER><a name="3flash1-6.html"> <font size="8"><I>Results</I> </font size="8"></A>
</B></I> </CENTER></U>
<BR>
<b><center><i><font size="5">MRC Family Hour Campaign Gets Results</font size="5"></i></center></b>
<br>
<br>
<P>The Media Research Center's campaign to bring the spirit 
          of the Family Hour back to prime time television has achieved 
national attention and impressive results. 
<P>At the end of April, the MRC organized a coalition of United States 
Senators and Representatives to issue a bi-partisan challenge to the 
television networks to voluntarily bring back the spirit of the Family Hour. 
Over 70 members of Congress signed a letter urging network 
entertainment executives to voluntarily broadcast only shows advocating 
positive family values during the first hour of prime time. The letter appeared 
as a full-page ad purchased by the MRC in the show-business newspaper 
<I>Daily Variety</I>.
<P>MRC Chairman Brent Bozell followed up with a lobbying effort 
directed at ABC Entertainment President Ted Harbert asking him to renew the 
highly acclaimed family drama <I>Second Noah</I>, which debuted this past February 
and whose survival hung in the balance.The advertisement and lobbying effort had demonstrable results.
 <P>On May 20, ABC announced that <I>Second 
Noah</I> would be included on its fall schedule, to air Saturdays at 
8 p.m. EDT. Subsequently, the show's creator and executive producer, 
Pamela Long, enthusiastically thanked Bozell and the MRC, writing that 
the <I>Daily Variety</I> ad &quot;struck just the 
right chord. And Ted Harbert...heard you loud and clear.&quot;       
<P>Bozell's &quot;eloquent letter to Mr. Harbert had a definitive impact on 
the decision-making process at the network,&quot; echoed Jacqueline 
Lovejoy, the show's publicist. &quot;[His] voice 
was powerful, and it was heard.&quot;
<P>Brandon Tartikoff, chairman of New World Television, 
<I>Second Noah</I>`s production company, has also 
recognized the MRC's work on the program's behalf. Tartikoff told 
<I>Flash</I> that &quot;support by Brent Bozell and his 
joint efforts with members of Congress... not only influenced ABC's decision 
to pick up the show, but also influenced the placement of 
<I>Second Noah</I> on Saturday nights, among the best times 
for family viewing.&quot; <BR>
<center><h2><I>The Top Ten Least and Most Family Friendly Shows of 
1995-'96</I></center>
</h2>
As MRC studies have shown, while the number of youth-targeted prime time series incorporating pernicious content has increased, wholesome shows are also gaining strength. The MRC's Entertainment Division recently released its &quot;Top Ten&quot; list of the least family-friendly prime time shows, but also saluted several programs which respect and uphold traditional values.
<P>
<P><I>The Top Ten Least and Most Family Friendly Shows of 
1995-'96</I>, which has been distributed to thousands of 
journalists, is the culmination of thousands of hours of television analysis. As 
of press time, this annual season-end tally has received widespread coverage 
in several major media outlets, including <I>USA 
Today</I>,<I> The Washington Post</I>, and the<I> Los Angeles 
Times</I>. It was even mentioned on the<I> Tonight 
Show</I>. 
<h3><P><B><center>The Top Ten Worst Shows:</center></B></h3>
<P>1.<B><I>Married...with Children</B></I> (Fox) Sunday 
9:00 p.m. EST
<P>The crudest comedy on prime time television, 
<I>Married</I> routinely ridicules the family. Every 
week members of the &quot;Bundys&quot; trade insults, 
celebrate promiscuity, and revel in bathroom 
humor; this raunchfest's dialogue is peppered with 
lewd punch lines about sex, masturbation, the gay 
lifestyle, and the lead character's fondness for pornographic magazines 
and strip clubs.
<P>2. <B><I>Friends </B></I>(NBC) Thursday 8:00 
p.m. EST
<P><I>Friends</I> has not toned down its adult content 
despite the show's shift to the earlier 8 o'clock hour. 
Virtually every episode revolves around sexual themes and contains 
inappropriate language. Each of the six central characters, 
all single twentysomethings, is sexually active. 
Additionally, the sitcom promotes gay parenting and same-sex marriages as viable options.
<P>3. <B><I>Roseanne</B></I> (ABC) Tuesday 8:00 p.m. EST
<P>Like<I> Friends, Roseanne</I>'s move to the 8:00 p.m. time slot has done 
little to mitigate the show's obnoxious content. The series' central characters 
are openly derisive of their parents; religion and the 
religious are mocked; foul language is frequent; 
premarital sex is condoned; and  gay marriage is championed.
<P>4. <B><I>Melrose Place</B></I> (Fox) Monday 
8:00 p.m. EST
<P><I>Melrose</I>'s randy regulars are constantly 
in and out of one another's beds, engaging in premarital and extramarital sex. 
Prime time's sexiest soap also showcases the gay lifestyle, with one gay 
character gaining a live-in lover this season.
<P>5. <B><I>A Season in Purgatory</B></I> (CBS) 
Mini-series
<P>Based on a Dominick Dunne novel, <I>Season</I> showcased members of 
a supposedly devout Catholic family promoting their faith in public 
while privately engaging in a vast array of premarital and extramarital 
affairs, rape, murder, and scandalous cover-up schemes. 
<P>6. <B><I>Central Park West</B></I> (CBS) 
Wednesday 9:00 p.m. EST (Canceled)
<P>One of the most hyped entries on last fall's schedule, 
<I>CPW</I> condoned premarital sex and adultery, 
and aired scenes containing foul language and explicitly sexual 
content. Fortunately, the acting and writing were so poor that very few viewers tuned in to its 
sordidness, and it was canceled.
<P>7. <B><I>The Dana Carvey Show</B></I> (ABC) 
Tuesday 9:30 EST (Canceled)
<P>The popular comedian shocked viewers and sponsors with 
obscenity-laden skits and extremely crude content. After many advertisers 
withdrew their support and ratings began to wane, ABC pulled the show off the air.
<P>8. <B><I>Cybill</B></I> (CBS) Sunday 8:00 p.m. EST
<P><I>Cybill</I>'s storylines frequently test the limits of decency. Dialogue is 
littered with foul language, sexual innuendo, and suggestive scenarios. 
The sitcom's regulars frequently belittle the institution of marriage. Casual sex 
-- even among teenagers -- is condoned.
<P>9. <B><I>Beverly Hills, 90210 </B></I>(Fox) 
Wednesday 8:00 p.m. EST
<P>While one character has steadfastly refused to lose her virginity, 
other members of <I>90210</I>'s tanned and trendy cast have been more than happy 
to promote premarital sex as a natural -- and completely inconsequential --  
fact of college life. The teen-targeted soap sends mixed messages on drugs. 
Some protagonists deride substance abuse, but rarely do they ever address the illegality of drug use.
<P>10.<B><I> Martin</B></I> (Fox) Thursday 8:00 
p.m. EST
<P>The sex lives of the two newlywed protagonists and their single 
friends serve as fodder for the raunchy humor pervading this sitcom. Most 
of <I>Martin</I>'s episodes contain dialogue fraught with sexual references and 
obscene language.

<br>
<h3><P><B><center>The Most Family-Friendly Shows of 1995-`96:</center></h3></B>
<P>
<br>
<B><I>Touched by an Angel</B></I> (CBS) Saturday 9:00 p.m. EST
<P>One of CBS' few success stories of the season, 
<I>Touched By an Angel</I> is the most outspoken proponent of 
traditional values on the prime time schedule. The inspiring drama 
showcases God's message of unconditional love, illuminates the power of 
prayer, and promotes compassion and strengthening family ties. 
<I>Touched By an Angel</I>, almost canceled last year 
by CBS, was the fastest growing series on the network and the second 
fastest growing show on prime time during the 1995-`96 season. 
<P><B><I>Second Noah</B></I> (ABC) Saturday 8:00 p.m. EST
<P>This mid-season replacement about a novelist, his veterinarian 
wife, and their eight adopted children is one of prime time's most 
pro-family offerings. Storylines depict respect for parental authority as the key to 
a strong family unit, and advocate premarital chastity, individual 
responsibility, and faith.
<P><B><I>Kirk</B></I> (WB) Sunday 8:30 p.m. EST
<P>The cornerstone of WB's family-friendly line-up, every episode 
of <I>Kirk</I> reiterates the importance of family. The title character, a 
young man suddenly charged with the upbringing of his three younger 
siblings, willingly makes many personal sacrifices to ensure 
that the children are receiving a sound moral upbringing. The show 
imparts the merits of hard work, faith, patience, and taking 
responsibility for one's actions.
<P>   <BR>
<B><I>Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman</B></I> (CBS) 
Saturday 8:00 p.m. EST
<P><I>Dr. Quinn</I>'s promotion of family values has 
endeared it to audiences of all ages. Marriage and 
family are staunchly promoted, as are honesty, compassion, and 
respect for parental authority. The drama boasts one of 
prime time's most positive clerics, &quot;the Reverend.&quot; A 
series regular, he is depicted as an intelligent, 
caring, and dedicated member of the community.
<P><B><I>Home Improvement</B></I> (ABC) Tuesday  9:00 p.m. EST
<P>This popular sitcom remains a reliable family staple. Focusing 
primarily on the relationships between a cable TV host, his wife, and their 
children, <I>Home Improvement</I> has taught valuable lessons about teenage 
drinking, honesty, respect, and the importance of education. One of prime 
time's foremost advocates of the institution of marriage, the show frequently addresses the 
challenges faced by the husband and wife and the 
steps they take toward strengthening their relationship. 
<P><B><I>Lois &amp; Clark: The New Adventures of 
Superman</B></I> (ABC) Sunday 8:00 p.m. EST
<P><I>Lois &amp; Clark</I> abandoned the suggestive 
dialogue and sexual references of its 1993-'94 inaugural season, and, 
in the words of series star Teri Hatcher, is now &quot;the family show 
to watch.&quot; The show's cleverly scripted storylines prove that 
television needn't appeal to the lowest common denominator to provide 
quality entertainment. Dialogue and fast-paced action sequences are free 
of offensive language and sexual innuendo, and the newly engaged 
protagonists promote premarital chastity.
<P><B><I>The Parent `Hood</B></I> (WB) Sunday 7:30 p.m. EST
<P>Another winning offering from WB, <I>The Parent 
`Hood'</I>s central characters provide positive 
role models for viewers of all ages. The happily married black 
couple, both successful professionals, teach their children 
that education, self-discipline and integrity are keys to 
success. The positive impact of a father in the household, 
family loyalty, and postponing sex until marriage are 
also underscored.
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>


<b><i><center><a href="flas1-6.html">"Flash"</a></center></i></b>

