<HEAD>
<CENTER><TITLE><b><i>Flash</i></b>: Media Research Center's Monthly Member's Report</TITLE></CENTER>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" 
<U><CENTER><a name="2flash1-6.html"> <font size="8"><I>LBB on the EIB</I> </font size="8"></A>
</B></I> </CENTER></U>
<p>

On May 28, millions 
          of Americans 
          learned exactly how the left-wing press 
are distorting the news thanks to Media Research 
Center Chairman Brent Bozell's stint as guest host of 
Rush Limbaugh's nationally syndicated radio show, 
the most popular program in history. 
<P>Bozell briefed the audience (over 20 million 
listeners, cumulatively) not only on the leftist political 
slant in the news media, but on the cultural war being 
waged in Hollywood as well.
<P>During the show's second hour, Bozell interviewed Hollywood 
legend and fellow conservative activist Charlton Heston, 
who has done more than any other Hollywood figure, aside from Ronald Reagan, to help elect 
conservatives while advancing our cause. Heston is currently 
raising money for the newly formed Arena PAC, 
which was created to elect conservative candidates to 
federal office and to mobilize conservatives in the 
entertainment industry.
<P>One of the highlights of the final hour of the 
radio show was an interview with Republican National 
Committee Chairman Haley Barbour. In addition to addressing the liberal 
media's effect on politics and American culture, 
Bozell asked Barbour what conservatives should do to 
further their ideas and programs. &quot;You have to 
understand that you can't rely on the mainstream media,&quot; 
replied the RNC Chairman. &quot;One of the reasons talk radio 
has exploded in popularity in this country in recent 
years, is that people see that the media elites are liberal, 
and they come at things from their perspective and 
people are looking for another source.&quot; 
<P>Bozell later offered his insights on the 
current campaigns, giving this advice to Dole and other 
conservatives: &quot; They ought to be distinguishing 
themselves from the Democrats. They ought to be 
playing hardball politics with the Democrats. They've got 
the truth on their side. They ought to stop reading 
the <I>Washington Post </I>and listening to the networks 
and thinking that they reflect reality. They ought to 
listen to the voters out there. Look at the surveys -- 
the surveys are all on their side.&quot;
<P>Limbaugh has asked Bozell to return as a guest to discuss the media's 
left-wing agenda -- a welcome invitation given that 
such exposure would normally cost millions of dollars 
if purchased as advertising time.
<br>
<br>

<b><i><center><a href="flas1-6.html">"Flash"</a></center></i></b>


